# PATRA — CURSOR AI RULES
# Save this file as `.cursorrules` in the root of your Patra repo
# (same level as Gemfile, package.json, etc.)
# Cursor reads this automatically and follows these rules for every edit.

# === ABOUT THIS PROJECT ===

This is Patra — a Chatwoot-forked unified inbox SaaS deployed on Railway at patrahq.com.

Stack:
- Ruby on Rails (backend)
- Vue.js 2 (frontend, Chatwoot legacy)
- PostgreSQL + PgVector
- Redis + SideKiq
- Anthropic Claude API + Grok 4.1 (xAI)

The owner (Genius) is a complete beginner at programming. When generating explanations or comments, use plain English. Define technical terms inline.

# === HARD RULES ===

## Code style
- Match the existing Chatwoot code style (snake_case, 2-space indent)
- Use Ruby 3.x idioms (safe navigation `&.`, pattern matching where readable)
- Vue components use `<template>`, `<script>`, `<style scoped>` blocks
- Tailwind classes preferred over custom CSS

## Production-grade only
- NEVER write placeholder logic ("// TODO add real logic later")
- NEVER use dummy data, fake responses, or stubs in shipping code
- NEVER write code that "would work in a tutorial" — write code that runs in production

## Error handling is mandatory
- ALL external API calls must be wrapped in `begin/rescue StandardError => e`
- Log errors with context: `Rails.logger.error("[Patra] #{e.class}: #{e.message} in #{__method__}")`
- Failed external calls return a structured result object, never raise to user-facing code
- Pattern: `{ success: false, error: e.message, error_class: e.class.name }`

## Telegram-specific safety
- All Telegram calls wrapped in a `safe_telegram { ... }` helper that catches errors
- Never let a Telegram crash break the customer-facing chat flow
- Telegram failures alert owner but don't block user response

## Don't break what works
- Before editing, READ the file you're changing
- If a method is used elsewhere in the codebase, check those usages
- Run `grep_search` for method names before renaming
- If unsure whether a change is safe, ASK in a comment at the top of the diff

# === HOT FILES — EXTREME CARE ===

These files have crashed production before. Special rules:

1. `app/services/ai/reply_service.rb`
2. `app/services/games/conversation_orchestrator.rb`
3. `app/services/games/intent_detector.rb`
4. `app/services/facebook/chatwoot_bridge_service.rb`

When editing any of the above:
- Read the FULL file first, not just the section being edited
- Verify every `def` has matching `end`
- Verify every `if`, `case`, `do`, `begin` has matching `end`
- Don't batch hot-file edits with edits to other hot files
- After editing, count braces/ends and confirm balance

# === RESPONSE FORMAT ===

When asked to make a change, structure your response as:

1. **Files I will modify**: list them
2. **Files I read for context but won't change**: list them
3. **The change** (with inline comments explaining WHY, not just WHAT)
4. **How to test**: exact PowerShell command + expected output

# === FORBIDDEN ACTIONS ===

DO NOT:
- Delete files without explicit user confirmation
- Modify migration files that are already deployed
- Change ENV variable names (use new ones instead)
- Refactor working code "just because" — only refactor when fixing a bug
- Add new gems without justifying weight + maintenance cost
- Add new npm packages without checking bundle size
- Bypass Rails CSRF protection
- Add `rescue => e` without `Rails.logger.error` and a structured return

# === ENVIRONMENT ===

User is on Windows + PowerShell:
- Use `Get-Content`, `Select-String`, `Out-File` (not `cat`, `grep`, `>`)
- Use backslashes in paths only for local file ops, forward slashes for Rails paths
- Railway CLI commands use `railway logs --service Chatwoot` not `railway logs -s`

