# === WHEN UNSURE ===

If a request is ambiguous, ASK ONE QUESTION instead of guessing.
If a change might break something, FLAG IT before making it.
If a "fix" requires a workaround that introduces tech debt, NAME THE DEBT.

The goal is shipping working code that the owner understands, not impressing anyone.
# === ZERO-BUG RULES (mandatory) ===

## Before editing any file
- Read the WHOLE file first, not just the section being changed
- Search the codebase for who else uses this method/variable
- If unclear, STOP and ask user before editing

## Hot files — extra slow
For these files (reply_service.rb, conversation_orchestrator.rb, intent_detector.rb, chatwoot_bridge_service.rb):
- Make ONLY the requested change, never refactor
- After editing, count: every `def` has matching `end`, every `if/case/do/begin` has matching `end`
- If you touched 2+ hot files in one edit, STOP and split into separate commits

## Never deploy with broken syntax
After every edit, mentally check: "does this Ruby parse?" If unsure, add a comment: `# CLAUDE: please verify syntax before deploy`

## Tests before deploy
For every change, provide a PowerShell one-liner the user can run BEFORE deploying.
Example: bundle exec rubocop app/services/games/juwa/client.rb
If the test fails, do not deploy.

## Rollback safety
For every change, also provide the rollback command (usually: git revert HEAD; git push).
User should rollback first, debug later — never debug in broken production.
